Oct. 6 - Covenant House, the Times Square shelter for homeless youngsters, will benefit from a buffet dinner, dancing and an auction from 7:30 to 10 P.M. at the Waldorf-Astoria. The evening also marks the 20th anniversary of the sponsoring organization, Who's Who International, a group of unmarried men and women who get together for parties and philanthropic causes. Tickets, $60, from 212-721-0413 or 212-330-0531. Saving Architectural Gems

Oct. 11 - The Historic House Trust of New York City was founded in June by 21 notable citizens in cooperation with the City of New York Department of Parks and Recreation. Their goal is to preserve 15 historic houses in the five boroughs. The first benefit for the trust will be held at Hyde Park Antiques, 836 Broadway at 13th Street, with a cocktail reception from 6 to 8 P.M. opening a furniture exhibition entitled ''Penwork, the Triumph of Line.'' There will be more than 70 examples of penwork, a decorative type of etching, from 1790 to 1830. Tickets, $100, from 212-360-8123. British Art Preview

Oct. 11 - In 1966 Paul Mellon founded the Yale Center of British Art. Since a building to house the collection opened on the Yale campus in 1977, Mr. Mellon has given the center 1,200 paintings and thousands of other artworks and books. Christie's, with Mr. Mellon, will hold a benefit preview of 26 paintings, including 17 from the center, that will be auctioned in London on Nov. 17 to benefit the center. Tickets for the cocktail reception and preview from 6 to 8 P.M., $50, from 212-546-1007. Saving Sight

Oct. 11 - The Glaucoma Foundation supports research and public education on the affliction that is a leading cause of blindness. Liv Ullmann will be the guest of honor at the third annual Black and White Ball at the Grand Hyatt. Cocktails at 7 P.M. will be followed by dinner and dancing. Tickets, $250, from 212-260-1000. Closer to a Cure

Oct. 12 - With the announcement in August of the discovery of the gene that causes cystic fibrosis, a cure for the disorder seems closer than ever. While 12 million Americans carry a defective form of the gene, a child must inherit it from both parents to be affected, something that happens to about 1,000 to 1,200 youngsters a year. The Cystic Fibrosis Foundation, which raises funds for research, will continue its efforts with ''An Evening With the Masters, a Culinary Gala'' at the Plaza. After cocktails at 6 P.M., there will be dinner and an auction of meals and lodging in top hotels in this country and Europe. Tickets, $500, from 212-986-8783.